shire, Wales":"Pwll, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch: occupational name for a cobbler.","Slovenian: nickname for a talkative person, from <i>lapati</i> ‘to babble’, or a topographic name from dialect <i>lap</i> ‘abyss’. Compare   Lapp   4."],"variants":[{"name":"Lapp","meanings":["German, English, and Dutch: from Middle High German and Middle English <i>lappe</i>, Middle Dutch <i>lap</i> ‘cloth, patch, rag’, a metonymic occupational name for a mender of clothes or shoes, or a nickname given to someone who wore ragged clothes or garments with loose folds, flaps, or hanging sleeves, or who had fleshy folds of skin on his face, neck, or body.","German: nickname for a simple-minded person, from Middle Low German <i>lappe</i> ‘fool’. This surname (in any of the two possible senses; see also 1 above) is also found in France (mainly Alsace, also Lorraine).","English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>lappe</i> ‘burdock’, perhaps for someone with a prickly character."]}]},{"name":"Llywelyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Llewellyn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewellyn","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Llywelyn</i>, derived from British Celtic <i>Lugubelinos</i>, itself from the divine name <i>Lugus</i> + an uncertain second element often used alone as a name. Through association with <i>llew</i> ‘lion’, it was altered to <i>Llewelyn</i>. This was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."]}]},{"name":"Ieuan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Iefan","meanings":["Later form of   Ieuan ."]},{"name":"Ifan","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ieuan Ap Llywelyn was born in 1310, in Pwll, Carmarthenshire, Wales. He had at least 2 daughters with Lleucu Verch Gwallter."},"et":{"1310–":"1310–Surnud","1311–Female":"1311–Surnud","1330–1405":"1330–1405","1337–1401":"1337–1401","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1337":"1337","1401":"1401","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1405":"1405","Ll Howlbwrch, Wales":"Wales","Flint, Flintshire, Wales":"Flint, Flintshire, Wales","Pwll, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Pwll, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1310–":"1310–Kuollut","1311–Female":"1311–Kuollut","1330–1405":"1330–1405","1337–1401":"1337–1401","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1337":"1337","1401":"1401","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1405":"1405","Ll Howlbwrch, Wales":"Wales","Flint, Flintshire, Wales":"Flint, Flintshire, Wales","Pwll, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Pwll, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fr":{"1310–":"1310–Décédé","1311–Female":"1311–Décédée","1330–1405":"1330–1405","1337–1401":"1337–1401","1310–Male":"1310–Décédé","1337":"1337","1401":"1401","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1405":"1405","Ll Howlbwrch, Wales":"Galles","Flint, Flintshire, Wales":"Flint, Flintshire, Galles","Pwll, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Pwll, Carmarthenshire, Galles","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Ieuan Ap Llywelyn est né en 1310, à Pwll, Carmarthenshire, Galles